<font color="#FF0000">SOMETHING FOR MY BROS</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 11 13:32:14 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Those Who Were There&quot;<br><br>
From the rank darkness of a sandbag tomb<br>
tired, straining eyes probe the ominous gloom<br>
Reflecting dim light from the sputtering flare<br>
caught in the grip of a thousand yard stare<br><br>
Fumbling damp fingers count the clips<br>
while each rasping breath escapes the lips<br>
and every painted face grows quiet numb<br>
while each heart rolls like a kettle drum<br><br>
Mosquitoes squirm in the oozing sweat<br>
no one slaps sharply at the stinging threat<br>
in the heavy silence that engulfs the fold<br>
Young men's thoughts turn dark and cold<br><br>
A fetid, sluggish breeze waifs the scene<br>
bring taints of feces, carbon and kerosene<br>
but the sweet smell of fear quells the senses <br>
all is focused on the barbed wire fences<br><br>
In a quick, furious flurry, the quietness erodes<br>
a machine gun rattles and a grenade explodes<br>
The enemy appears in the torn, twisted wire<br>
thrashing and twisting in the withering fire<br><br>
Tracers make the night a red spidery web<br>
while black, hostile forces charge and ebb<br>
each rifle barks, and every cannon growls<br>
ripping each human chest, exposing bowels<br><br>
While the enemy advances upon the barren hill<br>
it is then &quot;to live or die,&quot;  to be killed or to kill<br>
Finally, the ghastly, hot horror quietly subsides<br>
and each mourn dead brothers that lay by their sides<br><br>
The price of our freedom is too terribly high<br>
often paid for by &quot;All the way&quot; and &quot;Semper Fi&quot;<br>
And too few remember the gallant sacrifices made<br>
but the memories of those there, will never fade<br><br>
Copywrite 1998, Edward Ramon<br><br>

